@startuml channel-credential-lifecycle
' The life of a channel credential: the agent's own namespace, per-namespace fan-out, one Secret feeding both directions.
' Source of truth: docs/src/security/credentials.md
!include _style.puml

skinparam wrapWidth 420
skinparam maxMessageSize 340

actor "Platform\nengineer" as PE #FFE4B5

box "ns: team-support (the agent's own)" #FCFCFC
  participant "**Secret**\ndiscord-bot-credentials" as SEC #FFD580
  participant "**Agent** Pod" as AG #E6E6FA
end box

box "ns: team-sales" #FCFCFC
  participant "**Secret**\nslack-bot-credentials" as SEC2 #FFD580
end box

box "kaalm-system" #F0F4F0
  participant "**Operator** SA\nkaalm-controller" as OP #87CEEB
  participant "**Gateway** SA\nkaalm-gateway" as GW #90EE90
end box

participant "**Channel platform**\n+ callbackUrl receiver\n(outside)" as EXT #FFE4B5

note over PE, EXT #FFF8DC
  **The mirror of the LLM API key.** Same grammar, one
  structural difference: this Secret lives in the **agent's**
  **own namespace**, not in kaalm-system, and it **fans out**
  one per namespace. Everything else follows from that.
end note

== 1. Stored ==

PE -> SEC : create team-support/discord-bot-credentials
PE -> SEC2 : create team-sales/slack-bot-credentials
note over SEC, SEC2 #FFF8DC
  Namespace-scoped for organizational isolation:
  each namespace holds only the credentials for
  its own agents' channels. Created by the platform
  team or a provisioning service. Developers never
  need Secret access in their own namespace.
end note

== 2. Referenced ==

note over SEC, GW #FFF8DC
  The AgentChannel's webhook auth config names the Secret(s):
  **inbound** spec.webhook.auth.secretRef (bearer), or
  spec.webhook.auth.hmac.secretRef (HMAC)
  **outbound** spec.webhook.callbackAuth.secretRef or
  .hmac.secretRef, required whenever spec.webhook.callbackUrl
  is set (rule 25)
  Future platform types (v1.1) will use a top-level credentialsRef.
end note

OP -> SEC : the AgentChannelReconciler ensures **two**\nRoles + RoleBindings in the agent's namespace,\nboth resourceNames-scoped to exactly these\nSecret(s), both owned by the AgentChannel\nand torn down with it:\n**gateway Role:** get, watch\n**operator Role:** get, watch
note over OP, GW #FFF8DC
  **list** is deliberately omitted from both: RBAC
  resourceNames cannot constrain a plain list, so
  the verb would be dead weight. A name-scoped
  **watch** must set fieldSelector
  metadata.name=<secret> to satisfy the check.
  When auth and callbackAuth name the same
  Secret the Role lists it once; else both.
end note

== 3. Loaded ==

GW -> GW : watches AgentChannel\nresources directly
GW -> SEC : get + watch via the scoped Role,\non each new or updated AgentChannel
SEC -> GW : credential material
note over GW #90EE90
  Held **in-process**, split by direction.
  **One Secret, two consumers:**
  inbound **auth** feeds the
  adapter's **verifier**
  outbound **callbackAuth** feeds
  the adapter's **SendReply signer**
end note
GW -> SEC2 : get + watch via a **separate**\nscoped Role in team-sales: the reach is\nper-namespace, not blanket Secret access

OP -> SEC : get via its own scoped Role
SEC -> OP : credential material
OP -> OP : the AgentChannelReconciler validates\nonly that the **data** key is present
note over OP #87CEEB
  **Validation only.**
  **Retains nothing.** The operator never
  holds channel credential material.
end note

== In use: one Secret, both directions ==

EXT -> GW : inbound webhook POST
GW -> GW : **verifier** checks the signature\nusing the inbound **auth** material
GW -> AG : POST /v1/message, the normalized\nenvelope, carrying **no credential**
AG -> GW : reply
alt responseMode: async
  GW -> EXT : **SendReply** POST to callbackUrl,\n**signed** with the outbound\n**callbackAuth** material
else sync (the default)
  GW -> EXT : reply inline in the HTTP response.\nSendReply is not called, so the\noutbound material is never used.
end

== 4. Rotated ==

PE -> SEC : update the Secret in place
SEC -> GW : the gateway's Secret watch fires
GW -> GW : refresh in-memory credentials,\n**no restart**

legend bottom
  **Read this against the LLM API key figure.** There the Secret sat inside kaalm-system, was read by
  exactly two ServiceAccounts through a plain namespaced Role, and was never copied. Here the same two
  ServiceAccounts read it, but the Secret sits in the agent's namespace, so the grant has to be minted
  per channel, resourceNames-scoped, and garbage-collected with the AgentChannel. The agent Pod holds
  no credential material in either figure.
endlegend
@enduml
